# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bagel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Jewish women of New York City staged a boycott of kosher butchers in 1902 in response to a coordinated increase in price of kosher meat from 12 to 18 cents a pound.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] This increase was significant enough that many Jewish families could no longer afford to buy meat.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The protests, led mainly by immigrant Jewish women on Manhattan's Lower East Side, though controversial in their often-violent tactics, were largely successful and resulted in the lowering of the price of meat to 14 cents a pound.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The kosher meat boycott of 1902 developed as the Gilded Age was coming to a close.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The Gilded Age (1870–1900) in the United States saw powerful robber barons monopolizing a wide array of industries including the railroad, oil, steel and meat industries.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] These monopolies and trusts were able to dramatically increase prices in their respective industries, and prevented consumers from finding goods at a cheaper price.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Though Congress passed a number of antitrust laws in the 1890s, such as the Sherman Antitrust Act, these laws were not usually enforced and the government often sided with the powerful robber barons.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] At the turn of the 20th century, the meat industry was still under the control of robber barons who in 1902 decided to hike prices.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Initially, the Jewish butchers in New York City attempted to boycott the meat trust by refusing to sell meat, but the trust was too powerful and their boycott crumbled.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Thus the women of the Lower East Side Jewish community were forced to take matters into their own hands, staging a large boycott and convincing many people not to buy meat.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] These protests took place at a time when women were beginning to exert political influence.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In addition to the rise of women's suffrage movements, the end of the 19th century saw the number of middle class American women volunteering in clubs, professional societies, and local charities increase significantly.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] This trend in turn lent much more strength to women's suffrage movements and provided a model for women to exert their influence in other areas, such as in the kosher meat boycott.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In general, kosher meat tends to be pricier than non-kosher meat due to the various restrictions and requirements that come with it.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Adhering to the strict dietary laws of *kashrut* is a significant part of Orthodox Jewish life.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The laws of *kashrut* can be found throughout the Torah, Mishnah, Talmud and various halachic works.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The main criteria for a mammal to be kosher is that the animal must have split hooves and chew its cud.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Additionally, a certified butcher known as a shochet must slaughter the animal in accordance with Jewish law in a process known as shechita.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] After the shechita, the animal must be checked for any life-threatening wounds which could render the animal not kosher even after being properly slaughtered.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Finally many parts of the animal have to be removed such as certain fats and all the blood.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The meat is then salted in order to remove any remaining blood.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] This lengthy process and the many steps involved are what make kosher meat more expensive than non-kosher meat.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In 1902 the kosher meat was recorded to be 5-6 cents more expensive per pound than non-kosher meat, even before the price increased.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In 1902, although many American Jews began to assimilate and drop many of their religious practices, many still kept kosher.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Because of this, the increase in price for kosher meat had a relatively widespread impact.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] On May 11, 1902, around 400 kosher butchers on the East Side of New York organized a boycott of the meat trusts to put pressure on them to lower the cost of meat.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] However, the trusts were too powerful and the butchers ended their boycott.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In response to those unsuccessful attempts, the women of the Lower East Side Jewish community, led by Fanny Levy and Sarah Edelson, held a massive protest.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] On May 15, 20,000 protesters, mostly women, took to the streets to attack the butcher shops.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] They smashed shop windows, poured gasoline on the meat, lit it on fire and threw pieces of meat at police officers.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] By the end of the day, 85 people had been arrested, 75% of them women.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] After May 15, the protests expanded into local synagogues.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] During Sabbath services on May 17, two days after the street riots, a group of women stormed the podium of their synagogue to direct attention towards their cause.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] One woman got up on the synagogue podium, disrupted the Torah reading and lectured the community about the importance of joining the boycott.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] She then demanded that the men in the community compel their wives to join the protestors.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The strategy of promoting the boycott inside synagogues gained much attention and proved to be an effective means of gaining support within the Jewish community.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In the weeks following the riots, Jewish women of the Lower East Side continued to come up with creative ways to protest.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] They patrolled the streets of the Lower East Side in order to prevent other women from buying meat.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In a controversial but effective move, the protesters went door to door checking everyone's pots and pans to ensure that no one was secretly buying meat.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Anyone who was caught with meat was ridiculed and labeled a "scab." These tactics proved to be very effective.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Almost all purchases of kosher meats ceased.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] While the patrols went on, other boycott members worked around the clock to disseminate flyers and circulars in order to bolster support.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] One such circular read: "Eat no meat while the Trust is taking meat from the bones of your women and children." Women vigilantes went as far as to rob butcher shops and rid them of their meat.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The women involved in the protests also started a fundraising campaign to bail out imprisoned boycotters.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Due to the boycott's successful tactics, on May 22, the Retail Butchers Association (the kosher butchers association) realigned itself with the boycott campaign and ceased selling kosher meat in all their stores.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In addition, kosher restaurants throughout NYC removed meat from their menus until the prices came back down.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] By May 27, major Orthodox religious leaders had publicly affirmed support for the boycott, and by June 9 the prices dropped to 14 cents a pound.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Newspapers across NYC had many different reactions to the boycott.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] *The Forward*, a Yiddish newspaper, endorsed the boycott by praising them with a newspaper title "Bravo, Bravo, Bravo, Jewish women!" Many Jewish socialists were also sympathetic to the boycott.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] *The Tribune* also denounced the method of protesting, stating that the boycotters "made life miserable for the policemen." Ida Tarbell and Lincoln Steffens, two muckraker journalists, were pleased with the boycott's exposure of the robber barons and their corrupt policies.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The *New York Herald* came out with an article portraying the event as testimony to the impressive organizational skills of the women who put together the boycott.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] The boycott became so popular that its influence eventually spread to other Jewish communities in Harlem, Brooklyn, Newark, Boston, and Philadelphia, where similar protests took place.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] Many of the women who organized the kosher meat boycott of 1902 as well as their children played a significant role in the New York Labor movement, most notably the garment labor union.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In 1907 and 1908 rent boycotts broke out on the lower east side of Manhattan to protest high rent prices.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] They publicly acknowledged that the inspiration for the boycott and the tactics used derived from the meat boycott of 1902.
[src:bagel/1902-kosher-meat-boycott] In 1910, a meat boycott also occurred across the US primarily the Midwest, in part likely inspired by the 1902 kosher boycott.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] The English name, *bottarga*, was borrowed from Italian.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] The Italian form is thought to have been introduced from the Arabic *buṭarḫah* (بطارخة), plural form *buṭariḫ* (‏بطارخ‎), itself from Byzantine Greek ᾠοτάριχον (*oiotárikhon*), a combination of the words ᾠόν ('egg') and τάριχον ('pickled').
[src:bagel/abudaraho] 1500, as the Greek form of the word, when transliterated into Latin as *ova tarycha*, occurs in Bartolomeo Platina's *De honesta voluptate* (c.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] In an Italian manuscript that "closely parallels" Platina's cookbook and dated to shortly after its publication, *botarghe* is attested in the corresponding passage.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] The first mention of the Greek form (*oiotárikhon*) occurs in the 11th century, in the writings of Simeon Seth, who denounced the food as something to be "avoided totally", although a similar phrase may have been in use since antiquity in the same denotation.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] It has been suggested that the Coptic *outarakhon* may be an intermediate form between the Greek and Arabic, whereas examination of dialectical variants of the Greek ᾠόν 'egg' includes the Pontic Greek ὠβόν (traditionally where the mullets are caught), and ὀβό or βό in parts of Asia Minor.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] The modern Greek name comes from the Byzantine Greek, substituting the modern word αυγό for the ancient word ᾠóν.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Bottarga production is first documented in the Nile Delta in the 10th century BCE.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] In the 15th century, Martino da Como describes the production of bottarga by salting then smoking to dry it.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Bottarga is made chiefly from the roe pouch of grey mullet.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Sometimes it is prepared from Atlantic bluefin tuna (*bottarga di tonno rosso*) or yellowfin tuna.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] It is massaged by hand to eliminate air pockets, then dried and cured in sea salt for a few weeks.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Formerly, it was generally coated in beeswax to preserve it, as it still is in Greece and Egypt.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Orange and molded in wax or vacuum sealed, Tunisian bottarga is made from mullet eggs and is known as a sought-after product.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Initially a feature of the Judeo-Tunisian cuisine, it was introduced in Tunisia by Jews from Constantinople during Ottoman rule, as early as the 16th century.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Bottarga is produced in the Port Said area.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] In Greece, it is called *avgotaraxo* or *avgotaracho* (Greek: αβγοτάραχο-αυγοτάραχο) and is produced primarily from the flathead mullet caught in Greek lagoons.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] The whole mature ovaries are removed from the fish, washed with water, salted with natural sea salt, dried under the sun, and sealed in melted beeswax.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Avgotaracho Messolonghiou, made from fish caught in the Messolonghi-Etoliko Lagoons, is a European and Greek protected designation of origin, one of the few seafood products with a PDO.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] In Italy, it is made from bluefin tuna in Sicily, and from flathead mullet in Sardinia, where it is called Sardinian *butàriga*.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Its culinary properties may be compared to those of dry anchovies, although it is much more expensive.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Often, it is served with olive oil or lemon juice as an appetizer accompanied by bread or crostini.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] Bottarga is produced in Mauritania and Senegal.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] In Turkey, bottarga is made from grey mullet roe.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] It is produced in Dalyan, on the southwestern coast of Turkey, from the mature fish migrating from Lake Köyceğiz.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] There are various small producers elsewhere.
[src:bagel/abudaraho] For example, bottarga from Atlantic cod (*Gadus morhua*) is produced in northern Norway, where it is air-dried.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Other akara types includes Akara Awon (from beans and okro) and Egusi Akara (made from egusi seeds).
[src:bagel/acarajé] Another type of Akara product is Akara Ogbomosho (Akara chips) which are crunchy chips.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Brazilian acarajé is made from raw and milled cowpeas that are seasoned with salt, pepper and chopped onions molded into the shape of a large scone and deep-fried in dendê with a wok-like pan in front of the customers.
[src:bagel/acarajé] It is served split in half and stuffed with *vatapá* and *caruru* – spicy pastes made from shrimp, ground cashews, palm oil and other ingredients.
[src:bagel/acarajé] A vegetarian version is typically served with hot peppers and green tomatoes.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Acarajé can also comes in a second form called abará, in which the nutritious ingredients are steamed instead of deep-fried, similar to moi moi.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Acarajé serves as both a religious offering to the gods in the Candomblé religion and as street food.
[src:bagel/acarajé] In Sierra Leone, *akara* is composed of rice flour, mashed banana, baking powder, and sugar.
[src:bagel/acarajé] After mixed together, it is dropped in oil by hand, and fried, similar to puff-puff.
[src:bagel/acarajé] *Akara* is usually prepared for events like Pulnado (event held due to the birth of a child), a wedding, funeral, or party.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Acarajé sold on the street in Brazil are variously made with fried beef, mutton, dried shrimp, pigweed, fufu osun sauce, and coconut.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Today in Bahia, Brazil, most street vendors who serve acarajé are women, easily recognizable by their all-white cotton dresses and headscarves and caps.
[src:bagel/acarajé] They first appeared in Bahia selling acarajé in the 19th century.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Earnings from the sale of acarajé were used both to buy the freedom of enslaved family members until the abolition of slavery in Brazil in 1888; its sale additionally served as a source of family income.
[src:bagel/acarajé] The city now has more than 500 acarajé vendors.
[src:bagel/acarajé] The image of these women, often simply called *baianas*, frequently appears in artwork from the region of Bahia.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Acarajé, however, is available outside of the state of Bahia as well, including the streets of its neighborboring state of Sergipe, and the markets of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Acarajé is essential ritual food used in Afro-Brazilian religious traditions such as Candomblé.
[src:bagel/acarajé] The first acarajé in a Candomblé ritual is offered to the orixá Exu.
[src:bagel/acarajé] They vary in size based on their offering to a specific deity: large, round acarajé are offered to Xangô; ones smaller in form are offered to Iansã.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Small, fritter-size acarajé are offered to Erê (deity), or child spirits.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Acarajé is used in Candomblé rituals in the states of Bahia, Rio de Janeiro, São Paulo, Pernambuco, Alagoas, Sergipe, and Maranhão.
[src:bagel/acarajé] It is closely related to acaçá, a similar ritual food made of steamed corn mush.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is a variety of acarajé fried in an oil other than palm oil; olive oil or other vegetable oils are generally used.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Acarajé de azeite-doce is used in Candomblé offerings to orixás with a ritual prohibition of the use of palm oil.
[src:bagel/acarajé] This variety is found in the states of Bahia and Rio de Janeiro.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Acarajé de Xangô (àkàrà tí Ṣàngó) is a variety of acarajé offered to the orixá Xangô, known as the òriṣà Ṣangó in the Yoruba culture.
[src:bagel/acarajé] It is made of the same ingredients as the common form but greatly elongated.
[src:bagel/acarajé] This variety is found on the ritual platter of amalá offered to Xangô.
[src:bagel/acarajé] This variety is found in the state of Bahia and in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:bagel/acarajé] Acarajé was listed as a national intangible historic heritage (*patrimônio nacional imaterial*), by the National Institute of Historic and Artistic Heritage in 2004; the role of *baianas* in the preparation and sale of acarajé was recognized in the same act.
[src:bagel/acarajé] In October 2023, Rio de Janeiro declared the fritter to be part of that city's cultural heritage.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] In Levantine cuisine, kibbeh is made by pounding bulgur wheat together with meat into a fine paste and forming it into ovoid shapes, with toasted pine nuts and spices.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] It may also be layered and cooked on a tray, deep-fried, grilled, or served raw.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The Syrian city of Aleppo can lay claim to at least 17 types of kibbeh.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] In Mesopotamian cuisine, versions with rice or farina are found.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Outside of Lebanon and Syria, versions are found in Cyprus, Egypt, Israel, Palestine, the Persian Gulf, Armenia, and Turkey, and among Assyrian people.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] It is also found throughout Latin American countries that received substantial numbers of immigrants from the Levant during the late 19th and early 20th centuries, as well as parts of North America.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The modern word *kibbeh* (كبة) is derived from the Arabic root k-b-b (ك-ب-ب).
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The use of *kubbeh* to designate stuffed food may have also been derived from the Akkadian language *kubbu*.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The 10th century cookbook by Ibn Sayyar al-Warraq referred to meatballs as *kubab* (singular *kubba*).
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] As noted by food historian Nawal Nasrallah, the earliest mention of modern kibbeh, made with a filled shell of ground meat and grains, is in the 18th century work *Taj al-'Arus min Jawahir al-Qamus*.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The text describes it as a disk of ground meat and rice flour made by the people of "al-Sham" (the Levant).
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] American Methodist missionary William McClure Thomson noted in his memoirs during his 1847 visit to Lebanon that kibbeh, then made by crushing wheat in mortar and pestle, was very popular.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] He described it as "the national dish of the Arabs", despite its association with the Levant.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Swedish Orientalist Jacob Berggren described 8 types of kibbeh in his 1844 dictionary, and also mentioned a proverb about its social importance: "[...], without our koubbé, we would all have died".
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The 1885 Beirut cookbook *Ustadh al-Tabbakhin* by author Khalil Khattar Sarkis provided 15 kibbeh recipes, including recipes for *kibbeh labaniyyeh*, *kiyyeh bil siniyyeh*, *kibbeh mashwiyyeh*, among others.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The *Comparative Encyclopedia of Aleppo* by Syrian author Khayr al-Din al-Asadi (completed in 1971, published posthumously in 1981) described 58 different kinds of *kibbeh*.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Kibbeh labaniyeh (Arabic: كبة لبنية) is a variant of kibbeh cooked in a yoghurt sauce and served over rice.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] *kibbeh mishwiyyeh* (Arabic: كبة مشوية) is kibbeh that is grilled rather than fried.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] In Lebanon, meatless versions of kibbeh exist, and are sometimes called "poor man's kibbe".
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The stuffing is made with onions, walnuts, and wheat.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] *Kibbet samak*, made using fish, is popular among Sunni Muslims in North Lebanon.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Potato *kibbeh* is a variation of kibbeh in which potato is mixed with the bulgur.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] It is often assembled in three layers: a potato layer, followed by the meat filling, then another potato layer on top.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Author Claudia Roden describes it as an "oriental shepherd's pie." It is especially popular in Lebanon.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The city of Aleppo, Syria, is known for its many varieties of *kibbe*.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] *Kibbeh sajiyeh* (Arabic: كبة صاجية) is kibbeh shaped into a thin disk with a meat filling that is traditionally dipped in a yogurt sauce.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] A Syrian soup known as *kubbi kishk* consists of *kubbi* ("torpedoes" or "footballs") in a yogurt (*kishk*) and butter broth with stewed cabbage leaves.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Another soup, known as *kibbeh hamda*, consists of chicken stock with vegetables (usually leeks, celery, turnips and courgettes), lemon juice and garlic, with small *kibbeh* made with ground rice as dumplings.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] In the Syrian Jewish diaspora this dish is popular both for Pesach and as the pre-fast meal on the day before Yom Kippur.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Among Kurdish Jews, there is a kubba soup flavored with aromatic thyme leaves during winter.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] In Turkey, kibbeh is called *içli köfte*.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The outside shell can be made without or with tomato paste in different recipes.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] In Egypt, *kibbeh* is referred to as *kobeba* (Egyptian Arabic: كبيبة).
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Seafood variations of kobeba exist, such as shrimp kobeba, popular in Port Said.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Brazilian *quibe* is sometimes stuffed with Catupiry or another variety of *requeijão*, a sauce resembling ricotta and cream cheese.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Most Brazilian *quibe* uses only ground beef, but other variations use tahini, *carne de soja* (texturized soy protein), *seitan* (Japanese wheat gluten-based meat substitute) or tofu (soybean curd) as stuffing.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] In the Brazilian state of Acre, a variation of *quibe* called *quibe de arroz* (rice kibbeh) is made with a rice flour breading.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] It was created by Arab immigrants to Brazil who had no access to wheat in the remote Amazon region of Brazil.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] On Colombia's Caribbean coast, most local variations of the dish use ground beef instead of lamb, but the original recipe, or one with a mixture of beef and lamb, can be found served by the large Lebanese and Syrian population of the area.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The dish has acquired almost vernacular presence and is frequently served in social occasions at both Arab and non-Arab households.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] When served as an adopted local dish, it is offered often as a starter along with other regional specialties, including empanadas, deditos and carimañolas.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] The Dominican version was brought to the Dominican Republic by Lebanese immigrants.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Some regional Syrian and Lebanese dishes combine *kibbeh* with elements taken from Latin American cuisine; for example, it is typical of Syrian Mexicans to eat traditional kibbeh with salsa verde.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Kibbeh is considered by many to be a difficult dish to prepare, and as such, the quality of kibbeh is considered to be a benchmark for the skill of a cook in Iraq and the Levant.
[src:bagel/adom-kubbeh] Numerous mentions of kibbeh can be found in Aleppo Arabic folk proverbs.
[src:bagel/akkawi] Akkawi cheese is named after the port city of Akka (Arabic: عكّا).
[src:bagel/akkawi] Akkawi is commonly made with pasteurized cow's milk, but can also be made with goat or sheepmilk.
[src:bagel/akkawi] This cheese is largely produced in the Middle East, notably in Israel, Palestine, Lebanon, Jordan, Syria, Egypt, and Cyprus.
[src:bagel/akkawi] In these regions, people usually eat it with a soft flatbread during lunch and dinner.
[src:bagel/akkawi] Akkawi is hand-packed into square draining hoops and then cured in a salted whey brine for two days.
[src:bagel/akkawi] Akkawi is produced by heating milk to 35-40 Celsius, adding rennet, then leaving it to curdle for around an hour, after which the whey is squeezed out through a cheesecloth to drain the cheese.
[src:bagel/akkawi] The color is white and it has a smooth texture and a mild salty taste.
[src:bagel/akkawi] It is commonly used as a table cheese eaten by itself or paired with fruit.
[src:bagel/akkawi] The texture can be compared to mozzarella, feta or a mizithra, since it does not melt easily.
[src:bagel/akkawi] The texture and flavor is a result of its specific culturing from its curds that are kept together for a prolonged period longer than simpler tasting curd cheese such as Syrian cheese when akkawi is transformed into cheese.
[src:bagel/akkawi] The supply of akkawi has often been a problem in the Middle East.
[src:bagel/akkawi] During the Lebanese Civil War, dairy animals were slaughtered and the country had to import akkawi from Eastern Europe.
[src:bagel/akkawi] In Los Angeles, people used to make a substitute for akkawi by soaking feta cheese in several changes of water to desalinate it.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] The word *Striezel* is derived from Middle High German *strutzel*, *strützel*, in turn from Old High German *struzzil*.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] The first known mention of *Striezel* in the form of *Heiligenstriezel* comes from a *Nachrichtenbuech* (lit.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] 'news book') from Saxen in Upper Austria.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] The early versions of this bread were unbraided and made with a simple dough of wheat, eggs, fat and honey.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] In later years more complicated braided loaves became customary.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] In 1840, *Der Österreichische Zuschauer* described a custom among the Viennese to exchange the braided loaves on All Saint's Day.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] In 1929, the mastery of different types of braiding were added to the Bakers Master Examination Regulations in Upper Austria.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] In Austria and Bavaria *Striezel* is given to godchildren by their godfathers for All Saints' Day.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] This tradition has its origin in the ancient funeral cults in which mourning was expressed by a woman's cutting off her braided hair.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] In the 19th century, it was common to give this rich kind of cake to the poor due to a depiction by the Austrian (Styria) vernacular writer Peter Rosegger.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] Especially for children in rural areas, the present meant a recompense for poor food and times of hunger throughout the year.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] Also common (especially in Linz) was the superstition that the luck of the forthcoming year depends on the success of the pastry.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] If the yeast did not work and the dough did not rise, disaster or death were supposed to follow.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] Another practice of young men was to mock single women because of their singleness by giving them *Striezels* made of straw.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] In Dresden, the cake is now generally called *Dresdner [Christ]stollen*, *Stollen* being an unplaited German cake with a similar recipe.
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] However, its name in the city used to be *Dresdner Striezel*, and from 1434 gave its name to the Dresdner Striezelmarkt (Dresden Striezel Market).
[src:bagel/allerheiligenstriezel] A cake of that name is still (2014) baked in Dresden as a Christmas speciality.
[src:bagel/almadrote] Earlier recipes for almodrote may date recipes for a type of green sauce called *moretum* (believed to be the etymological origin of almodrote) in the Apicius, or it may be of Arabic etymology.
[src:bagel/almadrote] Concerning the latter, the evidence is based on modern lexicographical studies; it is not used for any of the sauces found in the 13th-century Andalusian cookbook, but may be derived from the Arabic term *almaṭrúq* meaning to pound.
[src:bagel/almadrote] During the Inquisition in the late 15th-century Fray Gonçalo Bringuylla was reported to have eaten "eggplant with *almadrote*".
[src:bagel/almadrote] In a later 16th-century cookbook the name of the sauce is altered to *capirotada*, though garlic is only present in one variation of the sauce.
[src:bagel/almadrote] Modern Sephardic cookbooks commonly contain recipes for vegetable casseroles with *almodrot* and *almodrote*.
[src:bagel/almadrote] These recipes may include white cheese or feta, sometimes combined with a firmer cheese like Gruyère, and eggs to thicken the sauce.
[src:bagel/bagel] A **bagel** (Yiddish: בײגל, romanized: *beygl*; Polish: *bajgiel* [ˈbajɡʲɛl] ⓘ; also spelled **beigel**) is a bread roll originating in the Jewish communities of Poland.
[src:bagel/bagel] Bagels are traditionally made from yeasted wheat dough that is shaped by hand into a torus or ring, briefly boiled in water, and then baked.
[src:bagel/bagel] The result is a dense, chewy, doughy interior with a browned and sometimes crisp exterior.
[src:bagel/bagel] Bagels are often topped with seeds baked on the outer crust—traditional choices include poppy and sesame seeds—or with salt grains.
[src:bagel/bagel] Different dough types include whole-grain and rye.
[src:bagel/bagel] The basic roll-with-a-hole design, hundreds of years old, allows even cooking and baking of the dough; it also allows groups of bagels to be gathered on a string or dowel for handling, transportation, and retail display.
[src:bagel/bagel] Bagels have been widely associated with Ashkenazi Jews since the 17th century; they were first mentioned in 1610 in Jewish community ordinances in Kraków, Poland.
[src:bagel/bagel] Bagels are now a popular bread product in North America and Poland, especially in cities with a large Jewish population.
[src:bagel/bagel] Bagels are also sold (fresh or frozen, often in many flavors) in supermarkets.
[src:bagel/bagel] Circular boiled-and-baked bread rolls (such as ka'ak, obwarzanek, taralli, and simit) have a long and diverse history across Europe and western Asia.
[src:bagel/bagel] Obwarzanek, a boiled-then-baked ring-shaped bread, was made by the 13th century Kraków baker's guild for Lent, as seen in royal family accounts from 1394.
[src:bagel/bagel] Another early mention of a boiled-then-baked ring-shaped bread, ka'ak, can be found in a 13th-century Syrian cookbook.
[src:bagel/bagel] The bagel may have been brought to Kraków by Bona Sforza, a woman from Bari, Italy, who became the Queen of Poland and Grand Duchess of Lithuania as the second wife of Sigismund the Old from 1518 to 1548.
[src:bagel/bagel] There is some evidence that the bagel may have been derived from pretzels made in Germany brought by immigrants to Poland.
[src:bagel/bagel] Linguist Leo Rosten notes in *The Joys of Yiddish*, that the first known mention of the Polish word *bajgiel* derived from the Yiddish word *bagel* in the "Community Regulations" occurs in Kraków in 1610, and that the food was given as a gift to women in childbirth.
[src:bagel/bagel] In the 16th and first half of the 17th centuries, the *bajgiel* became a staple of Polish cuisine.
[src:bagel/bagel] The name derives from the Yiddish word *beygal*, from the German dialect word *beugel*, meaning "ring" or "bracelet".
[src:bagel/bagel] In the Brick Lane district and surrounding area of London, England, bagels (locally spelled "beigels") have been sold since the middle of the 19th century.
[src:bagel/bagel] They were often displayed in the windows of bakeries on vertical wooden dowels, up to a metre in length, on racks.
[src:bagel/bagel] Bagels were brought to the United States by immigrant Polish Jews, with a thriving business developing in New York City that was controlled for decades by Bagel Bakers Local 338.
[src:bagel/bagel] They had contracts with nearly all bagel bakeries in and around the city for its workers, who prepared all their bagels by hand.
[src:bagel/bagel] The bagel came into more general use throughout North America in the last quarter of the 20th century with automation.
[src:bagel/bagel] Daniel Thompson started work on the first commercially viable bagel machine in 1958; bagel baker Harry Lender, his son, Murray Lender, and Florence Sender leased this technology and pioneered automated production and distribution of frozen bagels in the 1960s.
[src:bagel/bagel] Murray also invented pre-slicing the bagel.
[src:bagel/bagel] Around 1900, the "bagel brunch" became popular in New York City.
[src:bagel/bagel] The bagel brunch consists of a bagel topped with lox, cream cheese, capers, tomato, and red onion.
[src:bagel/bagel] This and similar combinations of toppings have remained associated with bagels into the 21st century in the United States.
[src:bagel/bagel] In Japan, the first kosher bagels were brought by BagelK from New York in 1989.
[src:bagel/bagel] BagelK created green tea, chocolate, maple-nut, and banana-nut flavors for the market in Japan.
[src:bagel/bagel] Some Japanese bagels, such as those sold by BAGEL & BAGEL, are soft and sweet; others, such as Einstein Bros. bagels sold by Costco in Japan, are the same as in the U.S.
[src:bagel/bagel] Bagels in the U.S. have increased in size over time.
[src:bagel/bagel] Starting at around 2 ounces (60 g), by 1915, the average bagel weighed 3 ounces (90 g); the size began to increase further in the 1960s.
[src:bagel/bagel] By 2003, the average bagel sold on a Manhattan coffee cart weighed around 6 ounces (170 g).
[src:bagel/bagel] At its most basic, traditional bagel dough contains wheat flour (without germ or bran), salt, water, and yeast leavening.
[src:bagel/bagel] Bread flour or other high gluten flours are preferred to create the firm, dense but spongy bagel shape and chewy texture.
[src:bagel/bagel] With a dough hydration of around 50–57%, bagel dough is among the stiffest bread doughs.
[src:bagel/bagel] Most bagel recipes call for the addition of a sweetener to the dough, often barley malt (syrup or crystals), honey, high fructose corn syrup, or sugar, with or without eggs, milk or butter.
[src:bagel/bagel] Leavening can be accomplished using a sourdough technique or a commercially produced yeast.
[src:bagel/bagel] This production method gives bagels their distinctive taste, chewy texture, and shiny appearance.
[src:bagel/bagel] In recent years, a variant has emerged, producing what is sometimes called the steam bagel.
[src:bagel/bagel] To make a steam bagel, the boiling is skipped, and the bagels are instead baked in an oven equipped with a steam injection system.
[src:bagel/bagel] In commercial bagel production, the steam bagel process requires less labor, since bagels need only be directly handled once, at the shaping stage.
[src:bagel/bagel] Thereafter, the bagels need never be removed from their pans as they are refrigerated and then steam-baked.
[src:bagel/bagel] The steam bagel results in a fluffier, softer, less chewy product more akin to a finger roll that happens to be shaped like a bagel.
[src:bagel/bagel] The dough used is intentionally more alkaline to aid browning, because the steam injection process uses neutral water steam instead of an alkaline solution bath.
[src:bagel/bagel] Bagels can be frozen for up to six months.
[src:bagel/bagel] According to a 2012 *Consumer Reports* article, the ideal bagel should have a slightly crispy crust, a distinct "pull" when a piece is separated from the whole by biting or pinching, a chewy inside, and the flavor of bread freshly baked.
[src:bagel/bagel] The taste may be complemented by additions cooked on the bagel, such as onion, garlic, sesame seeds, or poppy seeds.
[src:bagel/bagel] The appeal of a bagel may change upon being toasted.
[src:bagel/bagel] Toasting can have the effect of bringing or removing desirable chewiness, softening the crust, and moderating off-flavors.
[src:bagel/bagel] Traditionally New Yorkers do not toast bagels; they argue that if a bagel is well made and fresh it should never be toasted.
[src:bagel/bagel] Some New York City bagel shops, like Murray's in Chelsea and Ess-a-Bagel at 21st and Third Avenue, have had no-toasting policies.
[src:bagel/bagel] Toasting of bagels in New York City is considered a bastardization and sacrilege.
[src:bagel/bagel] Former *New York Times* food critic Mimi Sheraton called the practice of eating toasted bagels obscene.
[src:bagel/bagel] Gluten-free bagels have much more fat, often 9 grams, because of ingredients in the dough to supplant the wheat flour of the original.
[src:bagel/bagel] The New York bagel contains malt, is cold-fermented for several days to develop the flavors and enhance the crust, and is boiled in salted water before baking in a standard oven.
[src:bagel/bagel] The resulting bagel has a fluffy interior and a chewy crust.
[src:bagel/bagel] According to CNN, Brooklynites believe New York bagels are the best due to the quality of the local water.
[src:bagel/bagel] According to Brooklyn Water Bagels CEO Steven Fassberg, the characteristics of a New York bagel are the result of the recipe formula and preparation method.
[src:bagel/bagel] Different from the New York style, the Montreal-style bagel contains malt and sugar with no salt; it is boiled in honey-sweetened water before baking in a wood-fired oven.
[src:bagel/bagel] It is predominantly of the sesame "white" seeds variety (bagels in Toronto are similar to those made in New York in that they are less sweet, generally are coated with poppy seeds and are baked in a standard oven).
[src:bagel/bagel] Louis style bagel refers not to composition, but to a particular method of slicing the bagel.
[src:bagel/bagel] Louis style bagels are sliced vertically multiple times, instead of the traditional single horizontal slice.
[src:bagel/bagel] The slices range from 3 to 6 mm (0.12 to 0.24 in) thick.
[src:bagel/bagel] This style of bagel was popularized by the St.
[src:bagel/bagel] Louis Bread Company, now known as Panera Bread.
[src:bagel/bagel] Generally, the bagels are sliced into eight pieces using a bread slicer, which produces characteristically precise cuts (the bagel is not torn or crushed while slicing).
[src:bagel/bagel] This particular method of preparation increases the surface area available for spreads (e.g., cream cheese, butter).
[src:bagel/bagel] However, it decreases the portability of the bagel and prevents formation of sandwiches.
[src:bagel/bagel] Other bagel styles can be found elsewhere; Chicago-style bagels are baked with steam.
[src:bagel/bagel] American chef John Mitzewich has a recipe for what he calls San Francisco-style bagels which yields bagels flatter than New York-style bagels, characterized by a rough-textured crust.
[src:bagel/bagel] The traditional London bagel (or beigel as it is sometimes spelled and pronounced) is sweeter, chewier and has a denser texture.
[src:bagel/bagel] In Austria, *beigl* (often also spelled *beigerl* or *beugerl* in its diminutive form) are a traditional Lenten food.
[src:bagel/bagel] The rings are made from a yeasted dough, rolled out very thin and briefly boiled in salted water before topped with salt and caraway seeds and then baked.
[src:bagel/bagel] Depending on the region, they are sometimes baked to a very hard consistency, making them relatively brittle.
[src:bagel/bagel] Connected with it is the tradition of *Beiglreißen* (lit.
[src:bagel/bagel] 'ripping/tearing the *beigl*') at Easter where two people pull on opposite ends of a *beigl* until it breaks into two pieces.
[src:bagel/bagel] Tearing off the larger piece is meant to bring good luck.
[src:bagel/bagel] In Vienna, Eastern Lower Austria and Burgenland, *beugerl* has taken on the meaning of certain types of kipferl.
[src:bagel/bagel] While normally and traditionally made of yeasted wheat, in the late 20th century variations on the bagel flourished.
[src:bagel/bagel] Non-traditional versions that change the dough recipe include pumpernickel, rye, sourdough, bran, whole wheat, and multigrain.
[src:bagel/bagel] Other variations change the flavor of the dough, often using blueberry, salt, onion, garlic, egg, cinnamon, raisin, chocolate chip, cheese, or some combination of the above.
[src:bagel/bagel] Green bagels are sometimes created for St.
[src:bagel/bagel] A flat bagel, known as a 'flagel', can be found in a few locations in and around New York City, Long Island, and Toronto.
[src:bagel/bagel] According to a review attributed to New York's *Village Voice* food critic Robert Seitsema, the flagel was first created by Brooklyn's 'Tasty Bagels' deli in the early 1990s.
[src:bagel/bagel] Further, AIB-provided statistics for the 52-week period ending May 18, 2008, for refrigerated/frozen supermarket bagel sales for the top 10 brand names totaled US$50,737,860, based on 36,719,977 unit package sales.
[src:bagel/bagel] The AIB reported US$626.9 million fresh bagel US supermarket sales (excluding Wal-Mart) for the 52 weeks ending 11 April 2012.
[src:bagel/bagel] Fresh/frozen supermarket sales (excluding Wal-Mart) for the 52 weeks ending 13 May 2012 was US$592.7 million.
[src:bagel/bagel] The average price for a bag of fresh bagels was $3.27; for frozen it was $1.23.
[src:bagel/bagel] Many cultures developed similar breads and preparations, such as *bubliki* in Russia, Ukraine and Belarus, and *obwarzanek* (in particular *obwarzanek krakowski*) in Poland.
[src:bagel/bagel] Somewhat similar in appearance to bagels, these breads are usually topped with sesame and poppy seeds.
[src:bagel/bagel] The ingredients in these breads and bagels somewhat differ, as these breads are made with a different dough using butter, and sometimes also with milk.
[src:bagel/bagel] In Italy, *taralli* and *friselle* are breads similar to bagels.
[src:bagel/bagel] In Turkey, a salty and fattier form is called *açma*.
[src:bagel/bagel] The ring-shaped simit is sometimes marketed today as a Turkish bagel.
[src:bagel/bagel] Archival sources show that the *simit* has been produced in Istanbul since 1525.
[src:bagel/bagel] Based on Üsküdar court records (Şer’iyye Sicili) dated 1593, the weight and price of simit was standardized for the first time.
[src:bagel/bagel] Noted 17th-century traveler Evliya Çelebi wrote that there were 70 simit bakeries in Istanbul during the 1630s.
[src:bagel/bagel] Jean Brindesi's early 19th-century oil paintings about Istanbul daily life show simit sellers on the streets.
[src:bagel/bagel] Warwick Goble made an illustration of the simit sellers of Istanbul in 1906.
[src:bagel/bagel] Simit is very similar to the twisted sesame-sprinkled bagels pictured being sold in early 20th century Poland.
[src:bagel/bagel] *Simit* are also sold on the street in baskets or carts, as bagels were then.
[src:bagel/bagel] The Uyghurs of Xinjiang, China enjoy *girdeh nan* (from Persian, meaning round bread), a type of nan, the local bread.
[src:bagel/bagel] Another bagel-like type of bread is the traditional German *Dortmunder Salzkuchen* from the 19th century.
[src:bagel/bagel] Ka'ak al-Quds (better known in English as the Jerusalem bagel) is an oblong ring bread, usually topped with sesame seeds, with its origins in Jerusalem.
[src:bagel/bagel] Unlike the bagel, it is not boiled prior to baking.
[src:bagel/bagel] "Bagel" is also a Yeshivish term for sleeping 12 hours straight—e.g., "I slept a bagel last night." There are various opinions as to the origins of this term.
[src:bagel/bagel] It may be a reference to the fact that bagel dough has to "rest" for at least 12 hours between mixing and baking or simply to the fact that the hour hand on a clock traces a bagel shape over the course of 12 hours.
[src:bagel/bagel] In tennis, a "bagel" refers to a player winning a set 6–0; winning a match 6–0, 6–0, 6–0 is called a "triple bagel".
[src:bagel/bagel] "*Bublichki*" or "*Bagelach*" is a title of a famous Russian and Yiddish song written in Odesa in the 1920s.
[src:bagel/bagel] The Barry Sisters together with the Ziggy Elman Orchestra made it popular in the US in 1939.
[src:bagel/bagel] Today it belongs to the repertoire of klezmer, jazz and pop musicians.
[src:bagel/bagel] The term "bageling" refers to when a Jew uses a Jewish word or phrase in a conversation, or in the vicinity of a stranger who is also clearly Jewish, in order to inform them that they are also Jewish.
[src:bagel/bagel] The bagel is a major plot device in the 2022 science-fiction film *Everything Everywhere All at Once*.
